Beginning tomorrow, September 9, ALL students at Cole R-V will receive FREE breakfast and FREE lunch through DESE Seamless Summer Option and the USDA. The free meals will be available until December 31, 2020 or until the funds run out.

If your child is a resident of our district, but does not attend Cole R-V, you may request to pick up a free breakfast and/or lunch for any child under the age of 18. If you wish to order meals for children not enrolled at Cole R-V, you will need to contact Nina Kilson before 8:45 am daily at 573-498-4023 to request the meals. Meal pickup will be at 10:45 in the front school parking lot.

If you have already paid money on your child's lunch account, we will just keep that money in their account for when we start charging again. Ala Carte items will still be a charge because they do not qualify as part of the meal.

If you have any questions please call the central office at 573-498-4000.

post_text:
Help Us Keep Students Safe

Reminder:
Children should be visually inspected by parents/guardians for signs and symptoms of illness BEFORE loading on a school bus or coming to school, including a temperature check.

If anyone in your family or close acquaintance is experiencing COVID-19 symptoms, please keep your child home from school.

Here is a checklist that includes the symptoms of COVID-19.

• Fever over 100.0
• Chills
• Cough
• Headache
• Muscle aches
• New loss of taste or smell
• Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing
• Sore throat
• Close contact with a person with COVID-19 in the last 14 days

If your child develops any of the above symptoms with a fever while they are at school, the student, plus any immediate family members, will be sent home for:

• 72 hours with no fever, OR
• a doctor’s note clearing the child to return and no fever for 24 hours, OR
• a negative COVID-19 test is obtained.

CAR RIDER PICKUP/DROP OFF PROCEDURE CHANGES - EFFECTIVE 8/25/2020

As you are aware, it will be necessary to make some procedural changes to make sure we are keeping our students and staff safe at all times. After seeing the traffic congestion in our parking lots and on Highway 17, we have reevaluated our pickup and drop-off procedures to ensure safety of our students, and increase efficiency. Please see the attached map that illustrates the changes, effective today. Details have been emailed to all district parents and students, plus posted on the school website: www.coler-v.k12.mo.us.

We are working diligently to ensure minimal changes. Please be patient with us while we find what works best for our students’ safety.

Cole R-V uses Eagle Alerts, a text messaging system to quickly communicate with our district patrons. Eagle Alerts are designed for students, parents, and anyone else involved with the care of your child.

Starting at 10am today, Eagle Alerts based on categories are scheduled to send designated times, to ensure you are enrolled in our system appropriately.

Here are the times and categories for the Eagle Alert test messages:
10:00 am - School closing and early dismissal alerts
10:15 am - PreK-6th Elementary alerts
10:30 am - Grade 7-12 alerts

If you do NOT receive a text in a particular category listed above, please email the following information to pam.lepper@coler5.us:
1. Name
2. Phone Number
3. Cell Phone Carrier
4. Zip Code
5. Category you wish to be enrolled

post_text:
Transportation reminders for school starting on Monday, August 24 ....
1. Students will ride ONE bus, for both morning and afternoon routes.
2. Students will load back to front when possible.
3. Seating charts will be used, and families will sit in units when possible.
4. To reduce occupancy on the bus routes, parents may drop off or pickup students from school using our car rider lines.

In order to ease the burden on the first day of school and reduce the bulk and heaviness of backpacks, elementary students may bring in school supplies gradually during the first week.

If you need assistance with childcare, Cole R-V offers Eagle Care for grades PreK-6, starting August 31. Enrollment forms can be found on the district website, www.coler-v.k12.mo.us, or call (573) 498-4002 as soon as possible.

With the uncertainty with COVID-19, Cole R-V has developed three plans for educating our students during the 2020-2021 school year.

We will start this fall in PLAN A, in which all classes will take place in school buildings. Extra cleaning and safety protocols for staff and students will be followed. There will be no parents, visitors, and volunteers allowed in the building.

There are three important documents on the COVID page of the school website: www.coler-v.k12.mo.us.
1. Summary of all three reopening plans. More specific details will follow soon.
2. Help us keep kids healthy - handout for parents as we ask you to screen your children before sending them to school.
3. Map for car rider pickup/dropoffs to help ensure student safety.

Thanks for your patience and understanding during this uncertain time.

We are limiting the number of people in the building to one student and one parent. Sophomore, Junior and Senior students can pick up registration packets in the high school office anytime during the week of Aug 10-15. Any schedule changes will be by appointment only with Mrs. Adrian. Please contact her for appointment times at jess.adrian@coler5.us.

Junior High students can pick up registration packets anytime during the week of Aug 10-15. Changes to Junior High schedules will be taken care of the 1st day of school.

ALL PACKETS SHOULD BE RETURNED ON THE FIRST DAY OF SCHOOL.

All student schedules are available on the student/parent portal.

FRI, AUG 14
2020-2021 High School Registration

Missouri State High School Activities Association
July 16 at 3:41 PM ·

Yesterday, we shared information with our member schools on considerations. The MSHSAA Board of Directors and MSHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee (SMAC) offer this document as guidance on how our state association can consider approaching the many components of “opening up” sports and activities in preparation for the fall seasons, and beyond.

The risk of coronavirus transmission will still be present to some degree as school activities begin in August and possibly through the 2020-2021 school year. Students and their families, along with school personnel must recognize these risks and implement best practices to reasonably mitigate these risks.
READ HERE: https://bit.ly/3fCeVMu

post_text: Kelly Hoskins, pictured with his parents (Spencer and Laura Hoskins), his sister (Lanna), and his coaches (Pam Lepper and Spencer Webb), signs his letter of intent to compete in track and field at Truman State University. Kelly was Valedictorian at Eugene High School and also broke school records in Pole Vault and Triple Jump, while being an All-Conference, All-District, All-Sectional and State Qualifier in Track. Kelly intends to double major at Truman in Physics and Biology with plans to attend medical school afterwards with an emphasis in Radiation Oncology. Congratulations Kelly!

shared_text:
STEM Signing Day 2020 Virtual Award Event

Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry premiered a video.
June 26 at 8:08 AM ·

Today we're recognizing outstanding students from across the state for committing to further their education in the fields of science, technology, engineering and math. In partnership with our sponsors, we're awarding $25,000 in scholarships to students committing to study a STEM field at their postsecondary education institution of choice. Inspired by signing days for athletes, the Missouri Chamber Foundation’s Mathematics and Science Coalition launched the program in 2019 to raise awareness of STEM pathways for students beyond high school. Learn more at mochamber.com/signingday.

Thank you to our sponsors The Boeing Company, Orscheln Industries, Cerner Corporation, and the Missouri Department of Higher Education & Workforce Development!

post_text: Here is an update regarding the 2020 Eugene High School Alumni Banquet.
shared_text:
Roy Rutledge
May 12 at 7:29 PM ·

No one likes the current situation in the world, no one likes when tragedies happen, no one likes to see bad things happen to good people. Yet, normal will return. It will be a different normal but never the less, normal. The Cole R-V Alumni Association will have a dinner this year, just not in June. Our Alumni dinner for June 13th is cancelled and is being reschedule for September 12th at the Mary’s Home Knights of Columbus hall. This dinner is important for several reasons. First, it allows us to gather with friends, classmates and a group of fellow “Eagles” tell old stories and create new ones. Second, it is the single largest fundraiser for the Alumni each year. We have graduated from a single $200 scholarship in the old days to our current awarding of two $750 scholarships this year. We had several scholarship applicants this year and we are working with the school counselor to determine who will receive the scholarships. Please share this post on your social media platform. We look forward to seeing you at the annual dinner. Roy

STUDENT DRIVE THROUGH CHECKOUTS
Wednesday, May 6 - student last name A-K, 1:00-6:00pm
Thursday, May 7 - student last name L-Z, 1:00-6:00pm

LOCATIONS:
Elementary: front parking lot
JH/HS - back parking lot.
PTO trashbag orders - elementary teacher parking lot.

* Students should bring ALL textbooks, library books, sports uniforms and lunch money owed at this time. Please have these items in a bag marked with the student's name.
* Student belongings from desk/locker, plus any paid sports spirit apparel, will be delivered to your vehicle - please do not leave your vehicle.
* If JH/HS students have any belongings in the athletic locker rooms, you will be directed to park and the student will be allowed in the building one at a time to retrieve those items.
* If you cannot make your designated day, you may come on the other day.
* Any items not picked up within two weeks of these dates will be donated to our school's Caring Closet.

Any additional updates will be posted to www.coler-v.k12.mo.us.

Food Service Update as of 3/24:

After ongoing talks with DESE Food Service, Cole R-V can now deliver lunches to all students at your permanent address during the COVID-19 shutdown.

Cole R-V strongly encourages you to participate in this program. No student will be turned down.

Please make your reservation before Tuesday, March 24 at 9:00am if you wish to have lunches delivered for the duration of the COVID-19 shutdown.

You can make reservations in one of three ways:
1. Fill out this online form listed below.
2. Call your child's school office and let them know the address and number of children to serve.
3. Respond to this email with the address, number of children to serve, and your phone number.

If circumstances change, you may call either school office with the appropriate update.

If you have questions at any time, please contact us.

Junior High/High School office - (573) 498-4001
Elementary office - (573) 498-4002

post_text:
From Mrs. Burrow:

As the coronavirus continues, it's on the forefront of everyone's mind to work proactively to ensure our food service workers and students are safe and healthy.

The following temporary changes will start soon:

- Freshly prepared entree salads will be offered instead of a salad bar.
- Fruits and vegetables will be offered from behind the serving line, instead of self-serve by students.
- Prepackaged condiments will be offered.
- Bottled water and juice will be offered as ala carte in place of the drink station in our HS cafeteria. However, if your student would like to bring a water bottle, they will be allowed to fill it at our bottle filling station by the HS office. The procedure in the elementary cafeteria will be unchanged.

post_text:
Cole R-V believes that attendance is important for student success. However, we are receiving students that are running fever, and other symptoms that may be contagious. As a reminder, the here are a few conditions require exclusion from school:

- Fever of 100 or over, or had fever within 24 hours. Must be fever free for 24 hours without medication
- Vomiting
- Diarrhea
- Head Lice – students must be nit free and be checked by the school nurse before being allowed back in to school. Parents must bring child to school to be rechecked.
- Undiagnosed rash
- Red inflamed eyes (pink eye) until diagnosed and treated, if needed. Must be on medication for 24 hours before returning to school.

For a full list of conditions that require exclusion from school, please visit: www.coler-v.k12.mo.us

post_text: Cole R-V is moving ahead on improvements at our track! Weather permitting, we will have a 40' x 60' storage building and the shell of a 30' x 40' concession stand built by this spring. Future improvements will come in phases, and include drilling a well, adding electricity, bleachers, and restrooms. These photos and siding samples are available to view in the Central Office. We are really excited!

post_text: Our 7-12 students and staff enjoyed an AMAZING presentation by Marc Mero, a former WWE Wrestling Champion and Author of “How to be the Happiest Person on the Planet.” He reached the pinnacle of sports-entertainment success – then lost it all – but in the process discovered what’s most important in life. Everyone faces adversity. “It’s not how many times you get knocked down, it’s how many times you get back up. You can do anything you set your mind to!” He spoke to our students about his captivating journey, and inspired them to examine their life choices. His message also emphasized for all of us to feel a greater sense of appreciation toward their relationships and the “gift of time” – and are empowered to make a difference in their personal life, school, career, and community.

post_text:
Mrs. Kellogg's 7th grade math class recently completed "Escape Room" challenges! There were 8 challenges, and as a review each one was aligned with objectives from the unit. Students had to solve problems regarding proportions, discounts, taxes, and unit rates to crack a code. Each challenge had a different way to figure out a code, whether it be each number stands for a letter in the alphabet, some had wheels that spun to match the answer with the question for the code number, etc.
After the groups solved the code for one challenge they moved to the next one, we did this over a two day period instead of one so that they weren't rushed. The goal was to complete all of the challenges to "escape".

post_text: Mrs. Clarissa Stokes who teaches 5th grade at Eugene Elementary received a $700 grant from Target Field Trips for the 2019-2020 school year. Both 5th grade classes at Eugene made the trip to WOW on Friday, January 10th. They spent four hours in the wildlife and aquarium of the WOW museum. Students marveled over the hundreds of different types of animals and sea life on display. Students were able to interact and touch stingrays. In preparation for the trip to WOW, students studied many types of species and were each assigned a specific endangered animal in which they researched and presented in science class. Mrs. Stokes plans on writing for the grant annually to continue this opportunity for students at Eugene Elementary.

Congratulations to Mrs. Adrian's 6th grade class for winning the first prediction of postcards. Their prediction was 270 and we received 248 as of December. They will be treated to an extra recess.
Another prediction contest will begin this week through May 1.
The students are enjoying seeing the vast variety of locations!!!!
We will continue to collect postcards from EVERYWHERE------but here are the states that we would love to hear from yet: New Jersey- Louisiana- Idaho- Delaware- Connecticut- West Virginia- South Carolina....Know anyone here??!!
Thanks for helping us with this fun project!!!

post_text: Merry Christmas and Happy New Year from all of us at Cole R-V School District! As the year draws to a close, join us in reflecting on our many blessings. This is also a great time of year to find a way to bring joy to someone else this holiday season, especially if you have the comforts of a warm home and a loving family. We are all fortunate to live in such a great community. To our teachers, staff and students, take time to relax and rejuvenate during this holiday season. Finally, spend quality time with friends and loved ones. We will see you on January 6!

All donations are due by this Friday.

post_text: More pictures from our Veteran's Day assembly! The Class of 2022 presented a check for over $6000 from their "Short Stack for a Tall Cause" pancake dinner! Plus, Senator Mike Bernskoetter and Representative Rudy Veit issued proclamations from the Missouri House and Senate to the Class of 2021 and Class of 2022 for their support of the Central Missouri Honor Flight. Our students and guests enjoyed the message from our guest speaker, Dan Levasseur, plus a trip to the Freedom Memorial located in the Performing Arts Center.

post_text:
Winter weather is coming! Please make sure you are signed up for Eagle Alerts, it is the primary notification method for school closings or early dismissals. We encourage parents, guardians, grandparents or anyone who helps with childcare or transportation to sign up. Visit our website: www.coler-v.k12.mo.us to sign up!

IMPORTANT: If you are already subscribed to Eagle Alerts and have changed cell phone carriers (for example AT&T to Cricket) you MUST update your profile or you will not receive messages. If you need assistance, send us a FB message with your name, phone number and current carrier and we will be happy to help!

This week, October 21-25, is both National School Bus Safety Week and Bus Driver Appreciation Week! Take some time this week to thank your school's bus drivers for all they do.

In addition, take a look at this video https://youtu.be/rA1PyCWA4Mw, to learn why school buses are the safest form of student transportation.
